			<div id="mw-js-message" style="display:none;"></div>
						<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en"><span dir="auto">James Hunt</span></h1>
			<div id="bodyContent">
								<div id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
								<div id="contentSub"></div>
												<div id="jump-to-nav" class="mw-jump">
					Jump to:					<a href="#mw-navigation">navigation</a>, 					<a href="#p-search">search</a>
				</div>
				<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><p><a href="/w/index.php?title=Template:Use_dmy_dates&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Template:Use dmy dates (page does not exist)">Template:Use dmy dates</a>
<a href="/w/index.php?title=Template:Use_British_English&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Template:Use British English (page does not exist)">Template:Use British English</a>
</p>
<div class="dablink">For other people named James Hunt, see <a href="/w/index.php?title=James_Hunt_(disambiguation)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="James Hunt (disambiguation) (page does not exist)">James Hunt (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<p>{{#invoke:Infobox|infobox}}
</p><p><b>James Simon Wallis Hunt</b> (29 August 1947 &#8211; 15 June 1993)<sup id="cite_ref-autocourse_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autocourse-1">[1]</a></sup> was a British racing driver who won the <a href="/wiki/Formula_One" title="Formula One">Formula One</a> World Championship in <a href="/w/index.php?title=Template:F1&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Template:F1 (page does not exist)">Template:F1</a>. After retiring from racing in 1979, Hunt became a media <a href="/w/index.php?title=Pundit_(expert)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Pundit (expert) (page does not exist)">commentator</a> and businessman.
</p><p>Beginning his racing career in <a href="/wiki/Touring_car_racing" title="Touring car racing">touring car racing</a>, Hunt progressed into <a href="/wiki/Formula_Three" title="Formula Three">Formula Three</a> where he attracted the attention of the <a href="/wiki/Hesketh_Racing" title="Hesketh Racing">Hesketh Racing</a> team and was soon taken under their wing. Hunt's often action-packed exploits on track earned him the nickname "Hunt the Shunt." Hunt entered Formula One in <a href="/w/index.php?title=Template:F1&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Template:F1 (page does not exist)">Template:F1</a>, driving a <a href="/wiki/March_Engineering" title="March Engineering">March 731</a> entered by the <a href="/wiki/Hesketh_Racing" title="Hesketh Racing">Hesketh Racing</a> team. He went on to win for Hesketh, driving their own <a href="/w/index.php?title=Hesketh_308&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Hesketh 308 (page does not exist)">Hesketh 308</a> car, in both World Championship and non-Championship races, before joining the <a href="/w/index.php?title=McLaren_(racing)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="McLaren (racing) (page does not exist)">McLaren</a> team at the end of <a href="/w/index.php?title=Template:F1&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Template:F1 (page does not exist)">Template:F1</a>. In his first year with McLaren, Hunt won the 1976 World Drivers' Championship, and he remained with the team for a further two years, although with less success, before moving to the <a href="/w/index.php?title=Walter_Wolf_Racing&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Walter Wolf Racing (page does not exist)">Wolf</a> team in early <a href="/w/index.php?title=Template:F1&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Template:F1 (page does not exist)">Template:F1</a>. Following a string of races in which he failed to finish, Hunt retired from driving halfway through the 1979 season.
</p><p>After retiring from motor racing, he established a career commentating on Grands Prix for the <a href="/w/index.php?title=BBC&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="BBC (page does not exist)">BBC</a>. He was known for his knowledge, insights, dry sense of humour and his criticism of drivers who, he believed, were not trying hard enough, which in the process brought him a whole new fanbase. Hunt died from a heart attack aged 45. He then was inducted into the <a href="/w/index.php?title=International_Motor_Sports_Hall_of_Fame&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="International Motor Sports Hall of Fame (page does not exist)">International Motor Sports Hall of Fame</a> on January 29, 2014.
</p>
